# Harmonizer — Experiment Notes

Goal: reach **HDNet-class quality (~40 PSNR)** while keeping Harmonizer's
**resolution-independence and low memory** (HDNet is limited to ~1024×1024 before
memory blows up). The pitch is "HDNet-quality without HDNet's memory wall — works
at any resolution." Everything below serves that goal.

Discipline reminder: **change one thing per training run**, measured against a
fixed baseline (pipeline mismatches already fixed + new color filters). Don't stack
the decoder change, the backbone swap, and the regressor change in the same run, or
you won't know what helped. Log **peak memory + PSNR across resolutions (1024², 4K,
8K)** every time — that cross-resolution comparison vs HDNet is the whole point.

---

## 1. Decoder — what to try

You've moved from global filter arguments to a **U-Net that predicts a dense
per-pixel filter-coefficient map**, then upsamples the *arguments* (not the image)
to native resolution and applies the filters there. Memory stays bounded because
the network runs at ≤512 and only cheap coefficient maps are interpolated. This is
the right idea and it preserves the resolution-independence story.

Current plan: resize to 512×512 → encode down to 16×16 → skip connections back up to
256×256 → predict 256×256×k coefficient maps → interpolate to original size → apply
filters.

### What to try / decide

**Coefficient resolution is an ablation — don't assume 256 is best.**
Filter corrections vary *slowly* across space. HDRNet/bilateral-learning methods
deliberately predict **low-res coefficients** (16×16–32×32) and rely on smooth
upsampling, because low-res coeffs resist overfitting and spatial artifacts. Dense
256×256 coefficients give the network freedom to produce high-frequency per-pixel
variation — exactly where seams and banding appear. **Sweep 64 / 128 / 256** and
expect a sweet spot below 256.

**Bottleneck depth and coefficient resolution are separate knobs.**
You can bottleneck deep (16×16, more global context) *and* decode to moderate
coefficient resolution (≤128). Favor a **deep bottleneck + moderate coefficients**
rather than a shallow bottleneck. Harmonization benefits from global context;
the decoder + skips reconstruct spatial detail on the way up.

**Add a smoothness / TV regularizer on the argument maps from day one.**
Per-pixel arguments near the foreground mask edge can jump sharply → visible
halo/seam (`out = filtered*mask + original*(1-mask)`). A total-variation / gradient
penalty on the coefficient maps (plus optional feathering near the mask boundary)
is the standard fix. This is the most common failure mode of dense-coefficient
harmonization — plan for it.

**Audit each filter for spatially-varying-argument correctness.**
Some filters use *global* statistics internally and break when the argument becomes
per-pixel:
- `TemperatureFilter` computes global per-channel means (`meanR/G/B` over the whole
  image). A per-pixel temperature argument on top of a single global mean is
  semantically muddy — revisit the internals, not just the argument.
- Nonlinear filters (highlight/shadow are power curves) can turn a smoothly
  interpolated argument map into **banding** after the steep curve. Test on a
  high-res image with a smooth-gradient foreground.

**Rethink synthetic supervision so spatial DOF is actually trained.**
Eq. 8 synthetic composites use *global* arguments → the ground-truth coefficient map
is spatially constant → the synthetic per-stage loss gives **no signal** for spatial
variation. Spatial capability will only come from the real (GAN) iHarmony4 half via
the final-output loss. Either introduce spatial argument variation in the synthetic
scheme, or weight the final-image loss more heavily.

### Verification checklist
- Interp-arguments-then-apply produces smooth output for nonlinear filters (no banding).
- No seam at mask boundary (visual + TV-loss value).
- Peak memory stays flat as input resolution grows (the core claim).
- PSNR measured the **same way HDNet reports it** (resolution, MSE vs fMSE, which
  subsets) before claiming parity.

---

## 2. Backbones — what to try and why

Framing: the encoder is now a **U-Net contracting path feeding skip connections**,
not a global-feature trunk. EfficientNet already exposes five multi-scale outputs
(`enc2x, enc4x, enc8x, enc16x, enc32x` with channels `[16, 24, 40, 112, 1280]`) that
map naturally onto decoder skips. **Keep a pretrained encoder** — the decoder needs
semantic features to know *what* is mismatched, and ImageNet pretraining gives that
for free; a from-scratch encoder on iHarmony4-scale data is weaker.

Note: the repo's stem is **two-stream** (`_conv_fg` / `_conv_bg`, each 4-channel
`comp+mask` / `comp+(1-mask)`, then concatenated). Keep it — fg-vs-bg comparison is
the harmonization signal — but wire decoder skip channel dims to what the custom stem
actually outputs, not to stock EfficientNet numbers.

| Backbone | Why try it | Cost / caveat |
|---|---|---|
| **EfficientNet-B0** (current) | Baseline. ~21 MB, real-time, 8K-capable — the whole speed/size story. | Likely caps below 40 PSNR on its own. |
| **EfficientNet-B1/B2/B3** | Cleanest A/B: *only* capacity changes, same code path, same two-stream stem, same skip wiring. Richer features at modest size/speed cost. Isolates "does more backbone help at all." | Just change `from_name` + `enc_channels` + regressor/decoder input dims. |
| **EfficientNet-V2-S** | Better accuracy-per-FLOP than V1, trains faster/more stably. Good "is bigger worth it" test. | Slightly larger; re-check stage channel dims. |
| **ConvNeXt-Tiny/Small** | Best accuracy-per-param step up from B0 without going transformer. Strong global features, clean multi-scale outputs for skips. The "modern features" contender. | Re-wire two-stream stem + pick skip stages. Well-trodden though. |
| **MobileNetV3 / GhostNet** | *Opposite* direction — if decoder + new filters recover enough accuracy, go **smaller** than B0 to reclaim speed/size. On-thesis for the real-time/8K pitch. | Only if priority is the resolution story over raw MSE. |
| **MobileViT** (least-bad transformer) | If you specifically want to test the attention hypothesis at the backbone: hybrid conv+attention, small. | See transformer caveat below — rank below ConvNeXt-Tiny. |

### Why transformers (ViT/Swin) are probably the wrong tool here
- **Data-hungry.** iHarmony4 isn't huge; a from-scratch / lightly-tuned ViT often
  *underperforms* a convnet of similar size at this data scale. (Same dynamic that
  bit the self-attention regressor — attention needs scale you may not have.)
- The paper's IHT baseline **is** a transformer harmonizer, and Harmonizer beats it
  while being ~12× smaller — so a transformer encoder isn't obviously the path to
  better numbers.

### Honest expectation
With a decoder predicting dense coefficients, the backbone matters **more** than it
did in the global-scalar design (you now consume spatial feature maps, not one pooled
vector). But the **true ceiling is still filter expressiveness + spatial granularity**,
not encoder quality. Sequence it:
1. **B0 → B2/B3** first (cheapest, same code). If MSE barely moves, the backbone
   isn't your bottleneck — stop.
2. If B2/B3 helps, try **ConvNeXt-Tiny** as the modern-features step.
3. Only with a real reason + enough data/aug, try **MobileViT**.

---

## 3. Regressor — parallel heads + refinement pass

> **IMPORTANT — read first: decoder vs. scalar regressor are two different models.**
> The parallel-heads / cascade / refinement discussion below was about predicting
> **k global scalars** (one number per filter for the whole image). The **decoder**
> (Section 1) predicts a **256×256×k coefficient map** instead — k spatial maps, not
> k scalars. **If you commit to the decoder, the entire `CascadeArgumentRegressor`
> goes away and is replaced by the decoder + a coefficient head.** Don't build both
> a scalar regressor and a decoder in the same model — pick one. The scalar variant
> below is only worth keeping as a **separate ablation** (global vs spatial).
>
> **"Should the decoder use parallel heads?"** — slightly mismatched question. The
> decoder has no scalar "heads"; the k per-filter outputs are just channels of the
> decoder's final conv. The real decision is *how the k coefficient channels are
> produced and whether they interact*:
>
> - **Option A — single conv head (start here).** Decoder → one `Conv(C → k)` → k
>   coefficient maps. The spatial analog of "parallel": all k produced together from
>   shared features, no explicit interaction (they interact implicitly via shared
>   decoder features). Cheapest, correct first baseline. At pixel level there's far
>   more capacity than the 9-scalar bottleneck, so the overshoot problem is **less
>   severe** here — test A before adding machinery.
> - **Option B — per-filter conv branches.** Literal spatial parallel heads, one
>   branch per filter. Usually **skip it** — adds params and lets filters overshoot
>   (they don't see each other), same flaw as scalar parallel heads.
> - **Option C — single head + channel-mixing refinement (spatial analog of the
>   scalar "parallel + refinement").** Decoder → `Conv(C → k)` initial maps → small
>   refinement block (a couple convs over the k coefficient channels + decoder
>   features) → k *corrected* maps. Add this **only if Option A shows filters
>   fighting** (over-bright / over-saturated regions). Symmetric, no order bias.
>
> Bottom line for the decoder: **A first, add C if you see overshoot.** Section 3
> below applies only to a kept scalar-variant ablation.

### Background (why we're here)
- **Cascade regressor (paper, Eq. 7):** predicts filter args sequentially, each
  conditioned on the previous. Models filter interactions (brightness/highlight both
  push bright pixels) — paper ablation MSE 28.47 → 26.85. But it was **order-sensitive
  and over-weighted the first and last heads** (gradient/length imbalance in a chain).
- **Pure parallel heads:** fixed the first/last bias, but reintroduced the problem the
  cascade solved — filters predicted in isolation **accumulate and overshoot**. This is
  the paper's *worse* baseline (~28.47). Worse with the new color filters, which
  interact heavily.
- **Self-attention over filter tokens:** trained but **worse MSE**. At k≈9 tokens
  attention is data-hungry and under-supervised; tokens all seeded from the same pooled
  vector → weak keys/values → tends to collapse. Attention shines at dozens–hundreds of
  tokens, not ~9.

### The chosen approach: parallel heads → refinement
Permutation-symmetric (no first/last bias — fixes the original complaint) **and** models
decision-level interaction (what the cascade gave you):

1. **Parallel heads** produce initial arguments `a_1…a_k` independently from the
   pooled/global feature. No order bias.
2. **Form tokens** that include the *predicted argument values* `a_i` (not just
   features) — this is the key: later correction sees each filter's actual decision.
3. **1–2 refinement rounds** (small attention+MLP, or just a symmetric MLP mixer) take
   all k predictions together and output **corrected** arguments. Filters de-conflict
   symmetrically.

### Make the refinement trainable (this is where attention failed before)
- **Pre-LayerNorm + residual** around the refinement block. Without these a tiny
  attention/MLP on a regression target often won't beat the mean.
- **1–2 heads max**, correct `1/√d` scaling, **stack 2 small layers** not 1 (single
  layer underfits the interaction).
- **Give tokens distinct content:** seed each from a per-filter linear projection of the
  feature **+** its learned embedding **+** its initial predicted argument — not the same
  pooled vector for all.

### Cheaper fallback if attention still struggles at k≈9
**Symmetric MLP mixer:** concatenate all k initial predictions + the shared feature →
one shared MLP → k corrections. No attention machinery, far easier to train at this
token count, often **matches** attention when k is small. Treat MLP-mixer and
attention-refinement as the two real contenders; run both as ablations.

### Also check (likely root cause of the original cascade bias)
The paper's **dynamic loss strategy (Eq. 12)** exists precisely to stop the regressor
biasing toward particular filters. The first/last over-weighting you saw is the symptom
it targets — **confirm dynamic loss is actually on and working**. A disabled/broken
dynamic loss reproduces exactly that bias regardless of regressor design.

---

## Suggested ordering across all three

1. Lock the **decoder** with **Option A (single conv head)** — coefficient-resolution
   sweep + TV loss + filter audit + synthetic-supervision fix. This is the change with
   a real shot at 40 PSNR. (The decoder **replaces** the scalar regressor — not both.)
2. If Option A shows filters overshooting, add **Option C (channel-mixing refinement)**
   over the k coefficient maps. Optionally keep a **scalar variant (Section 3) as a
   separate global-vs-spatial ablation** — but that's a different model.
3. Swap **B0 → B3 / ConvNeXt-Tiny** last, to feed the spatial head better; measure delta.
4. Throughout: log **PSNR + peak memory across resolutions vs HDNet** — the contribution
   is *quality parity at any resolution with far less memory*, so that table is the paper.


